data.content:
# Migrating `BackgroundProcessor` to .NET 8

## Critical Breaking Changes

**`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+.** `ThreadAbortException` will never be raised. Your `catch` block and `Thread.ResetAbort()` are dead code. The `Stop()` method will crash at runtime.

This is the single most dangerous pitfall — the code *compiles* fine but fails at runtime.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces ThreadAbortException handling
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop cleanly — no ResetAbort equivalent needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);

        // Signal cancellation (replaces _running = false + Thread.Abort)
        await _cts.CancelAsync();

        // Wait with timeout — no Thread.Sleep, no Abort
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't finish in time — log warning, but do NOT
            // force-kill. There is no safe equivalent to Thread.Abort().
            Log.Warning("Worker did not stop within timeout");
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Pitfall |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Removed** — throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Compiles but crashes at runtime |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never thrown** | `catch` block is dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Removed** | Same as above |
| `volatile bool` for signaling | `CancellationToken` | `volatile` flag can't unblock a waiting call; tokens can |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `Task.Delay()` + `Task.WhenAny` | Sleep blocks the calling thread wastefully |
| `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run(...)` | Raw threads bypass the ThreadPool and don't propagate exceptions |

## If you can't make `GetNextItem` async

If the blocking call is a synchronous API you don't control:

```csharp
// Wrap the sync blocking call so it respects cancellation
private async Task<Item> GetNextItemAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Runs on a thread-pool thread; token lets callers give up waiting
    return await Task.Run(() => GetNextItem(), token);
}
```

> ⚠️ This doesn't interrupt the blocked thread — it only abandons the wait. If `GetNextItem` blocks on a socket/DB call, pass the token into *that* API for true cancellation.

## If you need `IHostedService` (ASP.NET Core / Worker Service)

For long-lived processors, inherit from `BackgroundService` — it manages the lifecycle for you:

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}
```

Register with `builder.Services.AddHostedService<BackgroundProcessor>()`. The host handles start/stop/cancellation automatically.
